custom_api_docs_error_note.message: Note: Error responses only occur when there is an internal server error or backend issue. Users not found or not yet analyzed should return success: true with flagType: 0 (Safe).

custom_api_docs_field_badge_color.message: (string, optional) - Background color (hex, rgb, or named color)

custom_api_docs_field_badges.message: (array) - Max 3 custom badge objects, each containing:

custom_api_docs_field_evidence.message: (array or null) - Evidence strings (e.g., from username, display name, description) or null

custom_api_docs_field_reasons.message: (object) - String-based reason names as keys, each containing:

custom_api_docs_field_reviewer.message: (object) - Optional. For crediting the human reviewer who verified the flag. Include username and displayName. Omit if automated/no human review.

custom_api_docs_flag_type_2_note.message: Flag type 2 (Unsafe) is the primary type you need for indicating inappropriate users. Use other flag types only if you have a specific reason for categorizing users differently.

custom_api_docs_intro.message: Implement two endpoints that return user status data. All responses must use the wrapper format with success, data, and error fields.

custom_api_docs_note_badge_colors.message: Badge colors support multiple formats: hex codes (#ef4444), RGB (rgb(239, 68, 68)), RGBA (rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.9)), or named colors (red). When color is not specified, badges use a default teal color. When textColor is not specified, badges use white text.

custom_api_docs_note_badges.message: Badges are small visual indicators that appear in user tooltips alongside the flag status. They display at the top of the tooltip to quickly communicate additional context about a user. Use badges to highlight important status information like verification status, priority levels, or special categories. Common examples: "Verified Unsafe", "High Priority", "Community Reported", "Auto-Detected".

custom_api_docs_note_batch_data.message: The data field contains an object where keys are user IDs (as strings) and values are user status objects.

custom_api_docs_note_batch_limit.message: We recommend implementing a limit of 100 user IDs per batch request to balance performance and response time.

custom_api_docs_note_batch_partial.message: Return only users that exist in your system. Unknown users should be omitted from the response.

custom_api_docs_note_cors.message: Your API must include the Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * header in responses to allow the browser extension to access your API.

custom_api_docs_note_flag_type_0.message: Return flagType 0 for users not in your system (not yet checked/unknown).

custom_api_docs_note_http_status.message: Return HTTP status 200 for all successful requests. Any other status code (4xx, 5xx) indicates a failure and the extension will treat it as an error.

custom_api_docs_note_https.message: All API endpoints must use HTTPS for security.

custom_api_docs_note_no_auth.message: No authentication is required. This is a fully public API.

custom_api_docs_note_reason_keys.message: Use descriptive string names for reason keys (e.g., "High Risk Pattern", "Suspicious Activity"), not numeric indices. These display directly in tooltips.

custom_api_docs_note_url_batch.message: The extension uses your configured URL directly (without modifications) for batch lookups.

custom_api_docs_note_url_single.message: The extension automatically appends /{userId} to your configured URL for single user lookups.

custom_api_docs_note_wrapper.message: All responses must use {success, data, error} format. When success: true, include data field. When success: false, include error message.

rotector_api_docs_batch_intro.message: Check multiple users in a single request. Maximum 100 users per batch.

rotector_api_docs_batch_note.message: Users not found in the database will not appear in the response. The data field contains an object where keys are user IDs (as strings) and values are user status objects.

rotector_api_docs_batch_rec_1.message: Use batch endpoints when checking multiple users (more efficient than multiple single requests)

rotector_api_docs_batch_rec_2.message: Keep batch sizes under 100 users per request

rotector_api_docs_batch_rec_3.message: Add delays between consecutive batch requests (recommended: 250ms minimum)

rotector_api_docs_error_handling_1.message: Always check the success field in responses

rotector_api_docs_error_handling_2.message: Handle network errors gracefully with appropriate retry logic

rotector_api_docs_error_handling_3.message: Log error details for debugging (error message, HTTP status, request ID if available)

rotector_api_docs_field_confidence.message: Confidence score (0.0-1.0) - AI model's certainty level

rotector_api_docs_field_confidence_reaso.message: Confidence score for this specific reason

rotector_api_docs_field_engine_version.message: Version of the analysis engine used

rotector_api_docs_field_evidence.message: Array of evidence strings or null if no direct evidence

rotector_api_docs_field_last_updated.message: Unix timestamp of last analysis update

rotector_api_docs_field_message.message: Detailed explanation of the violation pattern

rotector_api_docs_field_reasons.message: Object containing detailed violation analysis (omitted when flagType=0)

rotector_api_docs_field_reviewer.message: Information about the reviewer who verified the flag

rotector_api_docs_flag_type_1.message: Pending - User is queued for analysis

rotector_api_docs_flag_type_4.message: Integration - Related to API integration features

rotector_api_docs_flag_type_5.message: Mixed - Contains both safe and unsafe signals

rotector_api_docs_flag_type_6.message: Past Offender - Previously flagged but status changed

rotector_api_docs_intro.message: Integrate Rotector's AI-powered safety detection system into your own applications. This API provides access to user analysis data, flag types, confidence scores, and detailed violation reasoning.

rotector_api_docs_note_batch_all_users.message: All requested users are returned in the response. Users not yet analyzed or not in the system will have flagType 0 (Safe).

rotector_api_docs_note_batch_limit.message: Maximum 100 user IDs per batch request. Requests exceeding this limit will return an error.

rotector_api_docs_note_caching.message: Consider implementing client-side caching for user status data. The lastUpdated timestamp indicates when the analysis was last performed and can be used to determine cache freshness.

rotector_api_docs_note_cors.message: The API includes CORS headers that allow requests from all origins.

rotector_api_docs_note_field_reasons.message: Present for flagged, mixed, or confirmed users (flagType 1, 2, 5, 6)

rotector_api_docs_note_field_reviewer.message: Present only for confirmed users (flagType 2) verified by human moderators

rotector_api_docs_note_field_version_com.message: Indicates whether the AI engine version used was latest or outdated

rotector_api_docs_note_http_status.message: Return HTTP status 200 for all successful requests (including non-flagged users with flagType 0). Error responses with other status codes (4xx, 5xx) only occur for internal server errors or backend issues.

rotector_api_docs_note_https.message: All API requests must use HTTPS. HTTP requests will be rejected.

rotector_api_docs_note_no_auth.message: No authentication required. This is a fully public API.

rotector_api_docs_note_response_time.message: Best case: ~50ms. Average: ~200ms. Consider implementing appropriate timeout values based on these benchmarks.

rotector_api_docs_note_safe_users.message: For users with flagType 0 (Safe), the reasons field is automatically cleared to reduce response size. No detailed violation analysis is provided for safe users.

rotector_api_docs_note_support.message: For API support, questions, or to report issues, join the Rotector Discord server:

rotector_api_docs_note_timestamp_format.message: The lastUpdated field contains Unix timestamp in seconds (not milliseconds).

rotector_api_docs_note_version_compatibi.message: compatible - Analysis used a supported but not latest engine version
current - Analysis used the latest AI engine version
deprecated - Analysis used an engine version no longer supported
outdated - Analysis used a significantly older engine version

rotector_api_docs_note_wrapper_format.message: All API responses follow a consistent wrapper format with success (boolean) and either data (success) or error (failure) fields.

rotector_api_docs_rate_limit_1.message: The API uses Cloudflare rate limiting to ensure fair usage

rotector_api_docs_rate_limit_2.message: Rate limit errors return HTTP status 429. Implement exponential backoff for retry logic
